## 9 · HARD-WON RULES (Learned From 30+ Applications)

These are bugs and patterns discovered across 30+ application runs. **Do not violate these.**

### 9.1 JavaScript / Prototype Bugs
| Rule | Reason |
|------|--------|
| Never use `.ns` as a CSS class | Collides with notch sensor dot — use `.ndot` or `.ndot-n` |
| Apostrophes in single-quoted JS strings | Causes `SyntaxError` — always rephrase or escape |
| `makeShadow()` must be a factory function | PptxGenJS mutates the object — reusing causes corrupted slides |
| 8-digit hex alpha codes (e.g. `#00BFA544`) | Throw PptxGenJS warnings — cosmetic only, deck still generates |

### 9.2 Resume Formatting
| Rule | Reason |
|------|--------|
| `text-align:justify; text-align-last:left` | Prevents orphan-word stretching on last lines |
| Bold metrics MID-sentence only | Prevents "32%" dangling alone on last line |
| ≥6 words on every bullet's last line | Prevents wasted whitespace row |
| `@page { margin:.22in .28in }` | Proven tight-but-safe — do not increase |
| Never shrink font below 8.2pt | Illegible in print |
| Experience ≠ Case Study | They are separate proof points; conflating them kills the effect |

### 9.3 Design Patterns
| Pattern | How |
|---------|-----|
| Consumer screens (light/white background) | Add `.light` class on phone div for white-themed screens (e.g., checkout UX) |
| Dashboard/ops screens (dark background) | Default dark theme |
| Dual-accent within same company | Use different accent colors per case study (e.g., GrowthIQ = blue, PlanPass = purple) |
| Luxury brands | Cream/ivory backgrounds, navy headers, gold accents |
| Payment companies | Dark navy base, company's brand color as accent |

### 9.4 Content Accuracy
| Rule | Detail |
|------|--------|
| PhonePe 5K merchants | Driven by Instant Discount + EMI subvention — NOT by KYC automation |
| 30-min TAT | Applies to offer operations — NOT merchant onboarding |
| Navi | Distribution layer — does NOT own loan books or credit underwriting |
| Projected metrics | Use ranges ("15–20%") or label as "estimated/projected" — never state unverified numbers as fact |

